 so the import is valid.\n\nThe path is messy though, so let me design the actual `iam.go` file properly. I need to create a package in `output/internal/iam/` that imports both the `lifecycle` and `authz` sub-packages, then exposes a `NewMux()` function that returns an HTTP mux with all the routes registered. The tricky part is handling route specificity—I need to register more specific routes like `/users/{id}/roles` before the catch-all patterns like `/users/` to avoid conflicts between the lifecycle and authz handlers.\n\nLooking at what each package actually exposes, both `lifecycle.Handler()` and `authz.Handler()` return their own muxes with overlapping routes like `/users/`. Rather than trying to nest their muxes directly, I should extract the individual handlers from each package and register them explicitly in the top-level IAM mux so I can control the routing order and handle the path conflicts properly. a custom handler that checks if the path ends in `/roles` to route to authz, otherwise to lifecycle. Since both sub-packages already have their own internal muxes and handle `/users/` differently, I need to figure out how to coordinate between them—lifecycle handles `/users/{id}` while authz handles the roles portion.\n\nSetting up the dispatcher... The request routing is working correctly—the top-level handler inspects the path and delegates to either the lifecycle or authz mux accordingly. For the import paths, I need to map the file locations to their package imports: lifecycle and authz go under `internal/iam`, while the main iam.go file should use the `iam` package name to avoid circular dependencies.\n\nSince this is an integrate task, I'm skipping documentation and moving straight to the implementation—I'll structure iam.go with the necessary imports from net/http, strings, and the two subpackages, then set up the request routing logic.\n\nNow I'm defining the NewMux function to wire up the lifecycle and authorization handlers, registering routes for